07882nam a22009735i 9781400865222DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20142004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979755922  a(OCoLC)984687055  a(OCoLC)987927761  a(OCoLC)992454375  a(OCoLC)999369723  a97814008652227 a10.1515/97814008652222doi  a(DE-B1597)448028  a(OCoLC)891400524  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQC318.E57 E55 2014 7aMAT0030002bisacsh04a536.7300aEntropy /ced. by Andreas Greven, Gerald Warnecke, Gerhard Keller. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2014] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b21 line illus. 1 table.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Series in Applied Mathematics ;v4700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Contributors -- tChapter One. Introduction -- tPART 1. Fundamental Concepts -- tChapter Two. Entropy: a Subtle Concept in Thermodynamics -- tChapter Three. Probabilistic Aspects of Entropy -- tPART 2. Entropy in Thermodynamics -- tChapter Four. Phenomenological Thermodynamics and Entropy Principles -- tChapter Five. Entropy in Nonequilibrium -- tChapter Six. Entropy for Hyperbolic Conservation Laws -- tChapter Seven. Irreversibility and the Second Law of Thermodynamics -- tChapter Eight. The Entropy of Classical Thermodynamics -- tPART 3. Entropy in Stochastic Processes -- tChapter Nine. Large Deviations and Entropy -- tChapter Ten. Relative Entropy for Random Motion in a Random Medium -- tChapter Eleven. Metastability and Entropy -- tChapter Twelve. Entropy Production in Driven Spatially Extended Systems -- tChapter Thirteen. Entropy: a Dialogue -- tPART 4. Entropy and Information -- tChapter Fourteen. Classical and Quantum Entropies: Dynamics and Information -- tChapter Fifteen. Complexity and Information in Data -- tChapter Sixteen. Entropy in Dynamical Systems -- tChapter Seventeen. Entropy in Ergodic Theory -- tCombined References -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of entropy arose in the physical sciences during the nineteenth century, particularly in thermodynamics and statistical physics, as a measure of the equilibria and evolution of thermodynamic systems. Two main views developed: the macroscopic view formulated originally by Carnot, Clausius, Gibbs, Planck, and Caratheodory and the microscopic approach associated with Boltzmann and Maxwell. Since then both approaches have made possible deep insights into the nature and behavior of thermodynamic and other microscopically unpredictable processes. However, the mathematical tools used have later developed independently of their original physical background and have led to a plethora of methods and differing conventions. The aim of this book is to identify the unifying threads by providing surveys of the uses and concepts of entropy in diverse areas of mathematics and the physical sciences. Two major threads, emphasized throughout the book, are variational principles and Ljapunov functionals. The book starts by providing basic concepts and terminology, illustrated by examples from both the macroscopic and microscopic lines of thought. In-depth surveys covering the macroscopic, microscopic and probabilistic approaches follow. Part I gives a basic introduction from the views of thermodynamics and probability theory. Part II collects surveys that look at the macroscopic approach of continuum mechanics and physics. Part III deals with the microscopic approach exposing the role of entropy as a concept in probability theory, namely in the analysis of the large time behavior of stochastic processes and in the study of qualitative properties of models in statistical physics. Finally in Part IV applications in dynamical systems, ergodic and information theory are presented. The chapters were written to provide as cohesive an account as possible, making the book accessible to a wide range of graduate students and researchers. Any scientist dealing with systems that exhibit entropy will find the book an invaluable aid to their understanding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aEntropy. 7aMATHEMATICS / Applied.2bisacsh1 aBenatti, Fabio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDafermos, C. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorgii, Hans-Otto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreven, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreven, Andreas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHollander, F. den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutter, Kolumban, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeller, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeller, Gerhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLieb, Elliott H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaes, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Ingo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlivieri, E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRissanen, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUffink, Jos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVaradhan, S. R. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWang, Yongqi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarnecke, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarnecke, Gerald, eeditor.4edt